comments.text:
Gamers always want fps. That a cheepo-card from 2023 in nearly all cases beats Nvidia's holy 2025-cow of the budget market is pathetic. With a few adjustments the 7700XT will draw way less power, losing 5-10% fps. Even Intel's $279 B580 is getting into beating distance in several games: e.g. CP, Dying Light 2, Ratchet & Clank
To bring the weaker, older cards over a stable 60fps target from a 30+fps baseline, best use Lossless Scaling in combination with a not too slow IGPU or 2nd card, connected to the monitor. IMHO the result by lossless's AI-algo is fantastic. The RTX5090 can't do frame interpolation in an adaptive manner.
This way the cards (depending on game, settings) are running not at 100% utilization and the power draw shrinks massively, while obtaining some 200, 300... fps on the screen. The Latency in Dual Mode is surprisingly low, thanks to a render loop not blocked by doing scaling and fi. By some black magic it should be possible to run several render-cards in the old SLI pattern, with one slave-GPU doing the postprocessing and output for the others, but this time without micro-stuttering.
